body:
@Manishearth okay, using `.as_str() == "transmute"` instead.

Also added `[breaking-change]` to the commit, since it technically is. However, it's UB without it, so the breakage seems worth it.

Also, nominate for beta, since breaking at 1.1 seems impossible?

@alexcrichton I guess it's technically not undefined behavior to transmute if you already are using an `UnsafeCell`? Such as:

``` rust
unsafe {
    let val = &*self.foo.get();
    let val_mut: &mut Foo = transmute(val);
}
```

Though, at that point, you should likely just do `&mut *self.foo.get()`. Again, if this should always be an error, not something that can be turned off, I can move it to `intrinsicck`, if that seems better.

@tomaka 

> I'm not aware of this #[repr(C)] + Drop, but if it's a lint to warn about implementing Drop on types with a #[repr(C)], I'd be opposed to it as well. I was also opposed to pointers not implementing Send/Sync.

While at a high level these may seem similar, they do all have their own motivations. The drop lint is for the drop flag that @eddyb mentioned where your struct is implicitly larger than you otherwise stated because of the explicit `Drop` implementation. The `Send`/`Sync` changes were done to avoid having them only be opt-in (and _some_ types need to opt-out by default).

---

@nwin 

> I understand why you want a #[repr(C)] + Drop lint but I agree to tomaka opposing on this. That seems overly clucky. Was there a concrete case leading to this lint? Normally I would just assume that someone who uses #[repr(C)] + Drop on a struct does that for a reason.

@seanmonstar did you have motivation beyond #13146 and "this is probably a bad idea'?

@alexcrichton I think that quote from nwin is regarding the repr + drop lint, not this one?

As for motivation, it actually came from seeing it appear in crates on crates.io, such as the issue I [linked regarding pool](https://github.com/carllerche/pool/issues/2), which did this transmute in several places. I likewise started with a transmute in hyper's `OptCell`, until I noticed that line in the UnsafeCell docs, and scrambled to fix it.

I genuinely think that more often than not, it's a mistake because people don't realize it is undefined behavior, and pointing it out and suggesting `UnsafeCell` is the right thing to do. Those who think they know better, can add an `allow` in special cases.
